comment.text: Four-part historiated woodcut title border. Used by Johann Wagner of Bamberg (not established). CERL entry: Wagner, Johann (-1580) At head: Unidentified episcopal(?) coat of arms, flanked by figures of Sts. Narcissus and Ulrich at left and Sts. Afra and Hilaria at right. The coat of arms is probably related to Augsburg somehow, since the saints pictured are closely associated with that city. At foot: Christ on the cross flanked by (probably) the Virgin Mary and St. John, with phoenix (symbol of the resurrection) and the bronze serpent (cf. Numbers 21:1, a type of the crucifixion) at left and a pelican in her piety (symbol of Christ's sacrifice) and another illegible animal at right. At left: St. Matthew (writing his gospel), St. Mark (writing his gospel), St. Augustine (meeting a child while pondering the Trinity), St. Jerome (with lion), and St. Thomas Aquinas (writing his Summa) At right: St. Luke (writing his gospel), St. John (writing his gospel), Pope St. Gregory, St. Ambrose, and St. Bonaventure (writing)

comment.author: 65030572@N05
comment.text: I believe that this is "J.T. Saalmüller," the inscription of Johann Tobias Saalmüller (1741-1814), whose accepted form is in VIAF [1]. The VIAF source record in the database of the German National Library has an activity date of 1778 associated with him [2]. Johann Tobias Saalmüller was the pastor of the Ducal Court Church of Ehrenburg in Coburg, Germany, from 1780-1787. This was the court church of the Duchy of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha, of which Queen Victoria was a descendant via her mother [3] and of which her cousin and husband, Prince Albert, was also a descendant. Because it was a place of note, a book on the church's history was published in 1838, including biographical sketches of its pastors [4]. This book is available on Google Books, and at the beginning of the biographical sketch of Johann Tobias Saalmüller on page 147, it states that he was born in Römhild on 24 October 1741 [5]. This biographical sketch is the source of the dates of his service at the court church, mentioned above. It also states (p. 148) that in the year 1787, Johann Tobias Saalmüller returned to his "Vaterstadt" of Römhild as an official, where he served effectively in a series of posts until his death on 6 September 1814. Since this information places him in Römhild in both 1777 and 1797, it seems that he would be the author of the inscriptions in question. Th[?]. 85 W 250 Sum Tho: Mar[...] A[nn]o Chri[sti] M.DC.XII[...?] [...] Unpacking this to its individual components, we have at head one line of partially illegible Latin ms., struck through. It seems reasonable to conclude that we have another book from the library of Thomas Marschallus, rector of East Horndon, Essex, England, during the second decade of the 17th century. comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text:
Regarding the common binding and provenance of the volumes of the Goertz collection, J.H. Hanford ("The Goertz Collection," Princeton University Library Chronicle 17.1 (Autumn 1955), p. 40-45) has this to say:
In physical appearance the Goertz books ... have certain striking features of uniformity. Almost all are in parchment bindngs, almost all are labeled or stamped on the backstrip in similar color and tooling ... A bookplate having the pheasant on a hill of the Wrisberg arms and the coronet [i.e. Adelskrone mit zwei Perlen] and stag supporters of the Goertzes occurs regularly, in various sizes, on the inside of the front cover, and there is a carefully made bibliographical note written on the verso of the blank leaf preceding the title-page. The bindings are hard to date but would seem to be of the eighteenth century ... It seems likely that the big binding job was done under a single direction but over a period of years, and the same is true of the bibliographical processing. These notes are mainly but not entirely in a single hand ... (p. 41-42)
Both of these volumes (GC55 G9237 556k and GC55 G9237 563a) have the parchment binding, spine label, bookplate and bibliographical note (on title leaf) described by Hanford. Each also has a ms. contents list on the front free endpaper (in 2 different hands); that of GC55 G9237 563a is partially obscured by the bookplate of bookseller Ernst Conrad Stahl (1886-1966). The Goertz (or Görtz) family is another one of those [sarcasm]delightful[/sarcasm] onomastic-genealogical tangles with which German history is rife. They descend from a line originally named Schlitz. That name is first attested as Slitese in the early twelfth century; they took to calling themselves Schlitz von Görtz or von Schlitz genannt von Görtz in the early 15th century (cf. German Wikipedia and the NDB). Originally the family held land from the Benedictine abbey of Fulda in Hesse during the Middle Ages (and gave their name to the nearby town of Schlitz), but that allegiance dissolved in the Reformation. In the 18th century the family divided into two lines: von Schlitz genannt von Görtz, Hessian Standesherren (mediatised nobility) and Grafen with their seat at Schlitz, and Görtz-Wrisberg, Grafen with their seat at Wrisbergholzen near Hildesheim in Lower Saxony (formerly within the Duchy of Braunschweig-Lüneburg). As the bookplate with its emblems of both Wrisberg and Goertz attests, this latter branch was the one with the library, large portions of which were acquired by the Königliche Bibliothek zu Berlin in 1906 (cf. Hanford p. 41) and Princeton University in 1907-1908 (cf. the entry Dr. Richardson Goes Book Hunting at Princeton's Rare Books blog). Hanford further speculates "that the Goertz collection was in process of formation before the time of Karl Friedrich, Graf von Goertz und Wrisberg, who in 1735 married Katharina Eva Sophia, heiress of the Counts of Wrisberg, and whose descendants have lived in Wrisberg-Holzen to the present day. It apparently, however, received many additions during his lifetime and a few thereafter. He died in 1750." (p. 41).

comment.text: Erudito iuxta at[que] candido viro, D[omi]no Joanni Hagendorn [...] Ad: Carolus. D[ono]. D[edit]. Carolus, exiguu[m] magni tibi munus amoris Mittit, et aeternae pignus Amicitiae: [Gift inscription from Adamus Carolus to Joannes Hangendorn, with Latin distich. (Cf. this image of another copy of this work inscribed by Carolus.) Carolus was secretary to the Holy Roman Emperors Charles V and Ferdinand I; he also served as Ferdinand's ambassador in Hungary in 1540 (cf. E.F. Hirsch, Damiao de Gois (The Hague: Nijhoff, 1967), p. 58ff). A humanist, Carolus corresponded with (and occasionally presented inscribed copies of his books to) a number of his contemporaries, including Melanchthon and Beatus Rhenanus; he also edited the volume of elegaic poetry composed by Johannes Lange and others after the mysterious death of Kaspar Ursinus Vel, suspected of drowning himself in the Donau in 1538 (cf. G. Bauch, "Der humanistische Dichter Georg von Logau" in Jahresbericht der Schlesischen Gesellschaft für Vaterländische Cultur, v. 73 (1895), p. 30). Carolus was a particular friend of Jakob Spiegel, who dedicated his Lexicon juris civilis to him (cf. G. Knod, "Recensionen und Anzeigen [zu Briefwechsel des Beatus Rhenanus]" in Centralblatt für Bibliothekswesen 4. Jahrg., 7. Heft (July 1887), p. 313). DNB heading: Karl, Adam]

comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text: The "Joanni Hagendorn" of this inscription may possibly be identifiable with the "Joannes Hagendorn a Norimberga" (i.e. of Nuremberg) who appears on a matriculation list of the University of Vienna dated 13 October 1538. (The portion of the list in which his name appears is headed: "Sequuntur nomina puerorum regiae Maiestatis a cancionibus pro quorum omnium inscriptione oblatus est aureus Ungaricus.") Cf. F. Gall and W. Szaivert, eds., Die Matrikel der Universität Wien, III. Bd. (Wien: H. Böhlaus Nachfolger, 1971), p. 61.

It might be his inscription, but I don't know for sure.

Former coat of arms of the city of Breslau (now Wrocław, Poland), granted to the city by the Holy Roman Emperor Ferdinand I in 1503 and used until 1938. Cf. Wikipedia, which gives the blazon thus:
Quarterly, I: Gules, a lion rampant queue fourch erect facing sinister Argent, armed and langued Or outlined Sable, crowned Or outlined Sable; II: Or, an eagle Sable charged with across its breast and wings a crescent Argent upward pointing with a crosslet Argent attached rising from the middle; III: Or, a capital letter 'W' Sable serifed; IV: head and shoulders of St. John the Evangelist gardant Argent, with youthful face and long hair Argent outlined Sable and with halo Or outlined Sable, issuant from an inverted crown Or outlined Sable. Surmounting all at center a roundel Argent, double-bordered in Sable, charged with St. John the Baptist's head Argent, with beard and hair Sable, semi-gardant turned toward the dexter.
A somehwat stylized version of these arms is currently (since 1990) used by the city.

One of 71 woodcut illustrations by Tobias Stimmer from Matthias Holtzwart's Emblematum Tyrocinia, an emblem book printed by Bernhard Jobin in Strasbourg in 1581. For an analysis, see Michael Lailach, "'Der Gelehrten Symbola': Studien zu den Emblematum Tyrocinia von Mathias Holtzwart (Strassburg 1581)," Diss., Eberhard-Karls-Universität Tübingen, 2000. Lailach identifies this woodcut as a depiction of Asclepius and describes it thus:
Im Bild des "Emblema.XLVIII." ist ein alter Mann mit einem langen Bart und einer Kappe auf einer Art Thron dargestellt. Er ist von zwei Vögeln, die einen großen Ring und eine Art Ehrenmünze im Schnabel herbeitragen, und von einem Kamel, Esel und Stier umgeben, die mit Schalen und Fässern herantreten. Sie bringen also ehrende Gaben und Geschenke. Zur Rechten des Mannes sind noch ein Hund mit einem Geldbeutel und eine Katze, die auf unübersehbare Weise ihr Geschäft verrichtet, dargestellt. Der Mann schaut auf den Hund und hebt die rechte Hand mit geöffneter Handfläche dem Tier entgegen. Zur Linken des Mannes liegen hingegen ein Wolf und ein Lamm in Eintracht beieinander. (p. 100)
